{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Bad idea — example IS the argument",
    "content": "**Bad idea.** The 道德仁义礼 example is not an illustration of a point that could be illustrated by something else. It IS the argument. The author chose it because:\n\n1. The Laozi passage has a five-level hierarchy with a specific reversal structure (bottom-up construction misread as top-down generation). A generic Western example would need to be invented from scratch and would lack the authority of an actual classical text.\n\n2. The author explicitly says \"上述并非对《老子》的解释\" — this is NOT an interpretation of the Laozi. The author is using the passage because \"恰好出现了这种自形而上至形的阶梯\" (it happens to contain exactly this staircase from the metaphysical down to phenomena). Swapping it out would make it look like the argument depends on the specific example, when the author's point is that ANY such hierarchy works this way.\n\n3. The translation apparatus (glosses, romanization) is not a burden — it is exactly what the 文言 convention was designed for. Block-quote the Laozi, gloss the five terms on first occurrence, then run in plain English. The reader learns five words in two sentences. This is no harder than learning \"Dasein,\" \"Aufhebung,\" or \"differance\" — and Western philosophical readers do that routinely.\n\n4. Swapping the author's own chosen example for a translator-invented replacement crosses the line from translation into rewriting. The translator serves the text, not the other way around."
  }
}
